It’s a decent pizza counter across the street from NYU and the Jay Street subway exit - BOOM, it’s right there when you hit street level, you can’t miss it!  Pizza is precooked, and sitting in a glass case, like most of the pizza places in NYC.  Choose how many slices you want, and they heat it up for a few minutes.  The line looked long but it actually moved pretty quick - I didn’t wait long at all.  I had a slice of cheese and mushroom and I think it was between $4 and $5 (but they had a special - two slices and a fountain drink for about $5.95).  I didn’t want two slices, or a soda, so I kinda got screwed after I paid for my slice and my bottled water.  There’s also a minimum $10 order for credit card purchases - LAME!  The pizza was decent and it didn’t seem like it had been sitting out too long, but I just wouldn’t describe it as having bragging rights for NYC pizza.  The pizza counter is on street level, but if you go up one level, there is a diner style restaurant with a wide variety of dishes.  The seating was just about at capacity, but if you head upstairs one more level, you will find more seating available.  Again, it’s not the best pizza in NY, but it’s decent and quick.  Friendly counter service too.

If I could give 0 stars I would.  My coworkers and I ordered 7 pies and paid approx $150 and they were terrible most of the pizza was not eaten because it was so bad.  There was almost no sauce on them and for the toppings they charge over $20 a pie there was hardly any pepperoni on the pizza and on the Hawaiian the pineapple was definitely canned and disgustingly dry.  I called to let the manager know and he offered me two free margherita pies for my dissatisfaction and I said ok.  When I ordered the pies a few days later he told me he's only giving me one pie and will charge for the second, completely going back on his word.  Bottom line, very expensive and poorly made pizza and stupidly bad customer service.
